<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06036084 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06036084 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; FOOTBALL; CLUB; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  New York Giants defensive coordinator Bill Belichick returned to Cleveland forhis second interview in five days for the job as head coach of the Browns.;   Belichick, 38, accompanied by his wife, Debby, spent Monday evening withBrowns owner Art Modell.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  BROWNS AND BELICHICK HUDDLING FOR 2ND TIME  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  NFL Notebook  </MEMO><TEXT>     The Browns scheduled a news conference for later today regarding thecoaching job.;    Team officials declined to comment on the Monday meeting.&quot;We will have no comment on our head coaching search,&quot; said a team spokesman,Kevin Byrne.;    Belichick, in the days following the Giants' Super Bowl win,interviewed last week for head coaching vacancies in Cleveland and Tampa Bay.The Tampa Bay vacancy was filled Monday with the hiring of Richard Williamson,who had served as interim coach.;    The Cleveland Plain Dealer reported todaythat &quot;barring a last-second hitch in negotiations&quot; Belichick would be named tocoach the Browns today or Wednesday.;    Belichick has been in the league 16years. If hired, he would be the youngest coach in the NFL. At present,youngest is the Los Angeles Raiders' Art Shell, 44.;  DITKA COMING BACK: CoachMike Ditka and the Bears have reached agreement on a three-year contractextension, the Chicago Tribune said today.;    &quot;He did it last week,&quot; Ditka'swife, Diana, told the newspaper. &quot;We're going to be here for a while.&quot;;    Theteam planned to make a formal announcement today, the newspaper said.;   Ditka, 51, became coach Jan. 20, 1982. He led the Bears to a Super Bowlvictory in January 1986. He was named coach of the year following the 1988campaign, the year in which he suffered a midseason heart attack, and theBears had a 12-4 record.;    There was talk after last year that Ditka wouldleave Chicago, but the team bounced back in 1990, and Ditka coached the Bearsto their sixth NFC Central Division championship in the last seven years.;   The team finished 11-5 in the regular season and lost 31-3 to the New YorkGiants in the second round of playoffs Jan. 13.;  BUDDY UPDATE: Buddy Ryan'soptions are dwindling. The recently fired Philadelphia Eagles coach denied hetalked to Minnesota's Jerry Burns about the defensive coordinator positionwith the Vikings vacated by the firing of Floyd Peters. The Minnesota job isthe only defensive coordinator position open.;    Ryan, Peters and the Rams'Fritz Shurmur, three of the most successful defensive coaches of the 1980s,all find themselves out of work at the moment. The World League of AmericanFootball, the NFL's international spring venture, kicks off March 23. There isonly one coaching vacancy, in New York. Former Colts offensive coordinatorLarry Kennan was named head coach of the London team on Monday.;  ETC.: TheMinnesota Vikings named Monte Kiffin as defensive coordinator. . . . The NFLreleased the names of 29 underclassmen who are eligible for the draft, a listthat includes Curvin Richards, the No. 2 rusher in Pitt history, and prospectEric Swann, who never made it to college. Swann, a 6-foot-4, 300-pounddefensive lineman, played last year for the Bay State Titans in football'sminor leagues. Swann, 20, once was set to play for North Carolina State butwas ineligible under Proposition 48 after he failed nine times to score thenecessary 700 on the Scholastic Aptitude Test.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910205  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  February  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  554  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday February 5, 199100036084,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYR